y:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">The Memory of IAS (Institued for\r\nAdvance Studies) consists of 1000 memory location called words of 40 bits each.\r\nBoth data are instruction are stored their.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left:90.0pt;mso-add-space:\r\nauto;text-indent:-18.0pt;line-height:150%;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:\r\n108.0pt\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif;\r\nmso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;\">2.<span style=\"font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><!--[endif]--><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">Numbers are represented in binary\r\nform and each instruction is a binary code.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left:90.0pt;mso-add-space:\r\nauto;text-indent:-18.0pt;line-height:150%;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:\r\n108.0pt\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif;\r\nmso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;\">3.<span style=\"font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><!--[endif]--><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">Each number is represented by a\r\nsign bit and a 39 bit values.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" style=\"margin-left:90.0pt;mso-add-space:auto;\r\ntext-indent:-18.0pt;line-height:150%;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:108.0pt\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif;mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;\">4.<span style=\"font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\r\n</span></span><!--[endif]--><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">A\r\nword make also contain two 20 bits instruction with each instruction consisting\r\nof an 8-bit operation code (Opcode) specifying the operation to be perform and\r\n12 bit address designating one of the words or memory. (Numbered from 0-999) <o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\r\nline-height:150%;font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">&nbsp;</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:150%;\r\nfont-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">&nbsp;</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:150%;\r\nfont-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:150%;\r\nfont-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">&nbsp;</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;line-height:150%;\r\nfont-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">&nbsp;</span>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:203.75pt;line-height:150%\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>', 12, 8, 2),
(22, '2.1 Register Transfer and RTL', '21-register-transfer-and-rtl', '<h1 style=\"margin-left: 36pt;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><sub>RTL (Register Transfer Language)<o:p></o:p></sub></span></h1>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:36.0pt\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size:14.0pt;line-height:107%;font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif;\r\nmso-ansi-language:EN-GB\">A Digital system is discrete system having interaction\r\nof digital hardware models that accomplished a specific information processing\r\ntask. Digital systems differs in size and complexity from the integrated\r\ncircuit to a digital computers. The modules are constructed from digital\r\ncomponents such as control logic, arithmetic elements, registers, decoders etc.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\" style=\"margin-left:54.0pt;mso-add-space:\r\nauto;text-indent:-18.0pt;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo2\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size:14.0pt;line-height:107%;font-family:Symbol;\r\nmso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol;mso-ansi-language:\r\nEN-GB\">·<span style=\"font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\r\n</span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size:14.0pt;\r\nline-height:107%;font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB\">A\r\nMicro operation is elementary operation performed in the information stored in\r\none or more registers. The use of symbol instead of explanation provides\r\norganized operation sequence in a register. The symbolic notation is used to\r\ndescribe, the Micro Operation transfer among registers and such symbolic\r\nnotation is called Register Transfer Language (RTL).<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" style=\"margin-left:54.0pt;mso-add-space:auto;\r\ntext-indent:-18.0pt;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo2\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size:14.0pt;line-height:107%;font-family:Symbol;\r\nmso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol;mso-ansi-language:\r\nEN-GB\">·<span style=\"font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\r\n</span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size:14.0pt;\r\nline-height:107%;font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB\">A\r\nProgramming Language use to execute the sequence of Micro operation is called\r\nRegister Transfer Programming Language.<o:p></o:p></span></p>', 13, 8, 1),
(23, '1.1	DATA STRUCTURE', '11data-structure', '<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:150%\"><strong>Data\r\nstructure</strong> is a particular way of storing and organizing data in a computer\r\nso that it can be used efficiently. There are different ways to organize the\r\ndata such as organization of data into the list, queue, stack and tree, graph\r\nand so on.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:150%\">Different\r\ntypes of data structures are used for different types of applications, and some\r\nare highly specialized to specific tasks. Data structures are used in almost\r\nevery program or software system. Specific data structures are essential for\r\nmany efficient algorithms, and make possible the management of huge amounts of\r\ndata, such as large databases and internet indexing services. Some formal\r\ndesign methods and programming languages emphasize data structures, rather than\r\nalgorithms, as the key organizing factor in software design.<o:p></o:p></p>', 23, 9, 1),
